@ianvisits Gosh , remember that like it was yesterday. Sitting in the back of Dad’s car, persuading Mum to let me take a couple of trolleybus pictures with her camera and Dad to stop the car to let me do so. And, it was 1961, still got the negs.

@MrTimDunn As I recall, Lake Havasu only got half of it anyway. The old bridge was split down the middle across the river and taken down in two exercises, so that one half could remain in use while the other was demolished. I think the Arizona bridge is therefore only half the width.

@ltmuseum Shome mishtake, shurley? Firstly, it’s a bullseye, not a roundel, secondly there was nothing like this around in 1908. That was the time the first ‘bar & circle’ appeared but they were very different from this. The style of this bullseye is 1950s/60s.
@qikipedia Few, if any, towns in the UK have train stations but many have railway stations.

@ltmuseum Technically, it’s a bullseye. The ‘bar & circle’ device became known as the bullseye during the 1920s and this was official LT parlance until c1973 when a redesign christened it the roundel.
@ltmuseum And they’re not ‘tube’ stations. The Metropolitan Line is a surface and sub-surface line and its trains wouldn’t fit inside any of the tube tunnels!
@ianvisits Whilst we have no basic objection to the use of copyright images from our catalogues, an acknowledgement of the source would have been appreciated at least.

@MoTGM London buses were renumbered at each overhaul. The one in the museum was originally RM 1331 (331 CLT) but finished service with the identity of the bus lent to Manchester in 1963.
